The Rays open their 25th season this afternoon, hosting the Orioles at 3:10 p.m. at a sold-out Tropicana Field. Shane McClanahan will be on the mound for the Rays, in his first time on the opening day roster. Here is the Rays’ lineup, with rookie outfielder Josh Lowe, who was called back up after Austin Meadows was traded on Monday night, at DH. Lefty John Means is set to start for the Orioles. Diaz, 3B Franco, SS Ramirez, 1B Arozarena, LF B. Lowe, 2B Zunino, C J. Lowe, DH Margot, RF Kiermaier, CF McClanahan, P Orioles’ lineup: Mullins, CF Mountcastle 1B Mancini, DH Hays, RF Santander, LF Urias, 2B Mateo, SS Chirinos, C Gutierrez, 3B This is the 16th straight year the Rays have sold out their first home game of the season. The capacity of Tropicana Field is about 25,025, smallest in the majors. Here is a the timeline for the opening day festivities: 11:10 a.m. Stadium parking lots open 12:10 p.m. Ballpark & Rec stadium bar/restaurant opens 1:10: Stadium gates open 2:45: Orioles introductions 2:47: Rays introductions 2:53: Unveiling of 2021 AL East banner 2:57: National anthem, by saxophonist BK Jackson 3:01: Ceremonial first pitch, by Florida Highway Patrol trooper Toni Schuck — lauded for risking her life in stopping a driver who veered around barricades and was headed onto the Sunshine Skyway Bridge during the 10K running race on March 6 — and her husband, Scott, a Pasco County Sheriff’s sergeant 3:08: Rays take the field 3:10: First pitch, by Shane McClanahan • • • Sign up for the Rays Report weekly newsletter to get fresh perspectives on the Tampa Bay Rays and the rest of the majors from sports columnist John Romano. Never miss out on the latest with the Bucs, Rays, Lightning, Florida college sports and more. Follow our Tampa Bay Times sports team on Twitter and Facebook.